ation, social disorder, wrenching political changes, and shifting national boundaries swelled the ranks of the imprisoned and broadened the carceral reach of the state. This volume brings together theoretically sophisticated, empirically rich studies of key transitional moments that transformed the scope and nature of European prisons during and after the war. It depicts the complex interactions of both penal and administrative institutions with the men and women who experienced internment, imprisonment, and detention at a time when these categories were in perpetual flux.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aPrison administrationxHistoryx20th centuryxEurope. 0aPrisonsxHistoryx20th centuryxEurope. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, European. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh1 aCampion, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaplan, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Vito, Christian G, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrançois, Aurore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFutselaar, Ralf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFutselaar, Ralf, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrevers, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrevers, Helen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIrmer, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaqua, Alicia Quintero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVito, Christian G. De, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZwinkels, Esther, e